[2] Sirajganj, human
Date: Wed 29 Sep 2010
Source: bdnews24.com [edited]
<http://www.bdnews24.com/details.php?id=174783&cid=2>


The bout of anthrax has added 4 more victims at Kamarkhand Upazilla in
Sirajganj taking up the count to 218 in the district. The latest
victims are SB, 60, of Haluakandi village; LK, 16, and RK, 20, of
Dhopakandi village; and 'A', 18, of Shahbajpur village.

Statistics officer at Sirajganj civil surgeon's office Mohammad
Humayun Islam told bdnews24.com that Kamarkhand health and family
planning officer Mohammad Abdul Aziz identified the patients on
Wednesday [29 Sep 2010]. However, information published in the website
of the Institute of Epidemiology, Disease Control and Research on
Wednesday [29 Sep 2010] said the number of victims in the district was
6 until Wednesday, which made the number of total victims in the
country to 605.

The government has recently launched a vaccination programme to combat
the disease, but admitted that it will not be possible to run the
programme across the country before Eid-ul-Azha, which falls in late
November [2010].

Livestock minister Abdul Latif Biswas on 21 Sep 2010 had said: "It
(vaccination across the country) will take much time and so the
government will first run vaccination programmes in the 18
sub-districts (Upazilla) under 8 districts, affected with anthrax." He
said it could take up to 15 days to complete vaccination in the
districts.

The minister said 2.5 million vaccines are there in the 18
sub-districts and 1.9 million of them have so far been sent to the
grassroots level and the rest will be sent swiftly.

A 25-member national steering committee, led by Latif, and a 5-member
technical committee, led by a joint secretary of livestock ministry,
was formed the same day to conduct anthrax control activities. 4 more
committees were also constituted at district- and Upazilla-levels.

Latif said the government also posted veterinary surgeons at the check
posts of 10 corridors on the border areas to check entry of any
anthrax infected cattle into the country.

The monitoring of cattle in markets and cattle meat will be
intensified, he added.

